Reach and Speech
----------------

That last link is an interesting place to start:

If the question of what content should be moderated or banned is one left t=
o the service providers themselves, it is worth considering exactly what se=
rvice providers we are talking about.

At the top of the stack are the service providers that people publish to di=
rectly; this includes Facebook, YouTube, Reddit, 8chan and other social net=
works. These platforms have absolute discretion in their moderation policie=
s, and rightly so. First, because of Section 230, they can moderate anythin=
g they want. Second, none of these platforms have a monopoly on online expr=
ession; someone who is banned from Facebook can publish on Twitter, or set =
up their own website. Third, these platforms, particularly those with algor=
ithmic timelines or recommendation engines, have an obligation to moderate =
more aggressively because they are not simply distributors but also amplifi=
ers.

Internet service providers (ISPs), on the other hand, have very different o=
bligations. While ISPs are no longer covered under Title II of the Communic=
ations Act, which barred them from discriminating data on the basis of cont=
ent, it is the expectation of consumers and generally the policy of ISPs to=
 not block any data because of its content (although ISPs have agreed to bl=
ock child pornography websites in the past).

It makes sense to think about these positions of the stack very differently=
: the top of the stack is about broadcasting =E2=80=94 reaching as many peo=
ple as possible =E2=80=94 and while you may have the right to say anything =
you want, there is no right to be heard. Internet service providers, though=
, are about access =E2=80=94 having the opportunity to speak or hear in the=
 first place. In other words, the further down the stack, the more legality=
 should be the sole criteria for moderation; the further up the more discre=
tion and even responsibility there should be for content:

Note the implications for Facebook and YouTube in particular: their moderat=
ion decisions should not be viewed in the context of free speech, but rathe=
r as discretionary decisions made by managers seeking to attract the broade=
st customer base; the appropriate regulatory response, if one is appropriat=
e, should be to push for more competition so that those dissatisfied with F=
acebook or Google=E2=80=99s moderation policies can go elsewhere.

The crux of this case goes to the second paragraph, and algorithmic timelin=
es and recommendation engines. While it is noteworthy that the the genesis =
of Section 230 was primarily about protecting kids from porn, at least as f=
ar as Congressional intentions are concerned, it is pretty settled law at t=
his point that platforms are not liable for the content posted on them by t=
hird parties (in the U.S. anyways). The question in Gonzalez v. Google , th=
ough, is whether platforms are liable for their recommendations.

On one hand, from a purely legalistic perspective, I can definitely see the=
 case for =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D. Simply hosting content is distinct from pr=
omoting content into a user=E2=80=99s feed; while that promotion decision i=
s made by an algorithm, and not by a human, it is editorial in nature. On t=
he other hand, moderating some content but not other content is itself an e=
ditorial decision, and the entire point of Section 230 was to make clear th=
at a good faith effort to moderate content did not mean that the moderator =
assumed liability for all of the content on the platform. Should that apply=
 to the inverse?

From a product perspective meanwhile =E2=80=94 or call it the reality persp=
ective, if you wish =E2=80=94 a win for Gonzalez in this case would be a di=
saster for the way current platforms work. The fact of the matter is that o=
ne of the implications of there being zero marginal costs in terms of the p=
roduction and distribution of content is that there is an overwhelmingly am=
ount of content. This means that a lot of content, including spam, needs to=
 be deleted; it also means that a superior user experience comes from the p=
latform recommending content that you might be interested in.

To that end, should Gonzalez win, one possible option for platforms would b=
e to return to some sort of content neutral recommendation system, like a c=
hronological timeline. The revealed preference of users, though, which cons=
istently shows much higher engagement with algorithmic timelines (even if t=
heir stated preference is for chronological timelines), suggests that this =
will not be the preferred response; rather, I would suspect far heavier =E2=
=80=9Ccensorship=E2=80=9D of posts. I put =E2=80=9Ccensorship=E2=80=9D in q=
uotes because while I don=E2=80=99t think (more) potentially questionable p=
osts would be taken down =E2=80=94 that=E2=80=99s still protected =E2=80=94=
 I do think that there will be very aggressive controls on what gets promot=
ed.

It=E2=80=99s worth noting that there is an argument that this wouldn=E2=80=
=99t be the worst outcome: as I wrote in that Article, there is a distincti=
on between the right to be heard and the right to speak. What is necessary =
is firming up the right to speak: where I would like to see Congressional a=
ction, particularly if Gonzalez wins this case, is on two points:

* First, there should be no liability =E2=80=94 or monetary compensation re=
quired, for that matter =E2=80=94 for posting a link. Links are what the we=
b is built on, and it should stay that way; they are also an essential comp=
onent to communication and competition, and by extension, to the First Amen=
dment.
* Second, infrastructure companies =E2=80=94 and I would take a broad defin=
ition here, and include not just ISPs but also hosting and CDN providers =
=E2=80=94 should be given not just immunity but also be compelled to be con=
tent neutral.

To me this strikes the right balance: promotion is a unique capability, tha=
t is both exceptionally profitable and dangerous, and I=E2=80=99m ok with m=
oderation there. Simply being able to exist, though =E2=80=94 to have the r=
ight of speech, if not reach =E2=80=94 should be a right we all expect as A=
mericans.

The First Amendment and U.S. Speech Controls
--------------------------------------------

There is a broader point that is worth pointing out in the context of this =
case: much of the discussion around the moderation of content forgets that =
the First Amendment explicitly denies Congress any role in determining what=
 is moderated and what is not; the actual limitation for companies tends to=
 be some combination of legal costs, employee agitation, and popular sentim=
ent. This in turn explains why Section 230 was so essential to the Internet=
. On one hand, a huge portion of the Communications Decency Act of 1996, in=
cluding Title V, of which Section 230 was a, well, section, was thrown out =
because it was deemed a violation of the First Amendment. At the same time,=
 Section 230 not only shielded companies from liability but it also prevent=
ed cases from even making it to court =E2=80=94 and Section 230 itself was =
inspired by court cases that Congress disagreed with.

In short, Google v. Gonzales may be the only way that recommendation engine=
s are ever regulated in the U.S. This is how it might play out: first, if G=
onzalez wins, recommendation engines are liable for content they promote; c=
ompanies may win many cases that are brought under this interpretation for =
First Amendment reasons =E2=80=94 including Google, in this specific case =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the real burden will be in needing to fight these cases =
in the first place. What Congress will be able to do, though, is carve out =
new protections: this is where my ideas for protecting links and infrastruc=
ture come in. In other words, Congress needs Courts to carve out a negative=
 space in terms of speech, such that laws can be passed protecting speech, =
as opposed to Congress unilaterally limiting what can and cannot be said.

This is, admittedly, a somewhat bizarre way to regulate speech; I would arg=
ue, though, that it worked pretty well in the case of Section 230, and that=
 the value of the First Amendment is significant enough that it is worth th=
is relative inefficiency in coming to a societal consensus on how we want t=
he Internet to operate.

